\begin{greenbox}

\subsubsection*{Physical Meaning of \(f_c\) and \(\lambda_c\)}

The quantities

\[
f_c
\]

and

\[
\lambda_c
\]

represent the threshold values required for a photon to excite an electron across the semiconductor band gap.

They correspond to the minimum photon energy necessary for absorption.

\vspace{0.4cm}

The band-gap energy is related to the photon energy by

\[
E_g
=
hf_c
=
\frac{hc}{\lambda_c}
\]

where

\begin{itemize}

\item
\[
E_g
\]
is the band-gap energy

\item
\[
f_c
\]
is the critical (minimum) frequency

\item
\[
\lambda_c
\]
is the critical (maximum) wavelength

\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.5cm}

\textbf{Physical Meaning of \(f_c\)}

\[
f_c
\]

is the smallest photon frequency capable of exciting an electron from the valence band into the conduction band.

Since photon energy is

\[
E=hf
\]

higher frequency corresponds to higher energy.

Therefore,

\[
f<f_c
\]

implies

\[
hf<E_g
\]

meaning the photon does not possess sufficient energy to overcome the band gap.

\vspace{0.5cm}

\textbf{Physical Meaning of \(\lambda_c\)}

\[
\lambda_c
\]

is the largest wavelength capable of exciting electrons across the band gap.

Since

\[
E=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

larger wavelength corresponds to lower energy.

Therefore,

\[
\lambda>\lambda_c
\]

implies that the photon energy is too small to generate electron-hole pairs.

\vspace{0.5cm}

For the GaAs problem,

\[
f_c
\approx
3.42\times10^{14}\,\text{Hz}
\]

means photons with frequencies below this value cannot excite electrons across the band gap.

Similarly,

\[
\lambda_c
\approx
877\,\text{nm}
\]

means wavelengths longer than \(877\,\text{nm}\) will not be strongly absorbed by the semiconductor.

\end{greenbox}

