% ==================================================
% Tutorial 1 Solutions
% ==================================================

\subsection{Tutorial 1 Solutions - PART 1}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 1
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 1}

\begin{mainbox}

\textbf{Answer:} (b) In the opposite direction as the applied electric field.

\vspace{0.3cm}

The electric force on a charge is given by

\[
\vec{F} = q\vec{E}
\]

For a negative charge (\(q < 0\)), the force vector points opposite to the electric field direction.

Therefore, a negative charge experiences a force opposite to the applied electric field.

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 2
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 2}

\begin{mainbox}

\textbf{Answer:} (b) Loses electric potential energy when the particle moves in the direction of the electric field.

\vspace{0.3cm}

For a negative charge,

\[
\vec{F} = q\vec{E}
\]

Since \(q < 0\), the electric force acts opposite to the electric field.

When the particle moves in the direction of the electric field, the electric force acts opposite to the displacement. Therefore, the electric field does negative work on the particle.

Using

\[
\Delta U = -W_{\text{field}}
\]

a negative value of work implies that the electric potential energy decreases.

Thus, the correct statement is (b).

\end{mainbox}

\subsection*{Solution 3}

\begin{mainbox}

The ranking of the changes in electric potential energy is

\[
\boxed{II > I = IV > III}
\]

\vspace{0.4cm}

The electric field points to the right, so the electric potential decreases in the direction of the field.

For an electron,

\[
\Delta U = q\Delta V
\]

where \(q=-e\).

\vspace{0.3cm}

\textbf{Diagram I and IV:}

Points \(A\) and \(B\) are vertically aligned, so they are at the same electric potential.

Therefore,

\[
\Delta V = 0
\quad \Rightarrow \quad
\Delta U = 0
\]

\vspace{0.3cm}

\textbf{Diagram II:}

Point \(B\) is to the right of \(A\), so the electron moves in the direction of the electric field.

The electric potential decreases:

\[
\Delta V < 0
\]

Since the electron has negative charge,

\[
\Delta U = q\Delta V > 0
\]

Thus, Diagram II has the greatest increase in potential energy.

\vspace{0.3cm}

\textbf{Diagram III:}

In this case, point \(B\) is to the left of \(A\), so the electron moves opposite to the electric field.

Therefore,

\[
\Delta V > 0
\]

and since \(q=-e\),

\[
\Delta U < 0
\]

Diagram III has a larger horizontal displacement than Diagram IV, so it has the most negative change in potential energy.

\vspace{0.3cm}

Hence,

\[
\boxed{II > I = IV > III}
\]

\end{mainbox}


