\subsection*{Question 10}

\begin{mainbox}

Consider the setup shown where the (conventional) current is flowing to the right through a semiconductor, and a magnetic field is pointing out of the page.

A voltmeter hooked up as shown reads a Hall voltage of \(+10\,\text{mV}\).

Is this an \(n\)-type or \(p\)-type material?

Explain carefully.

\end{mainbox}

% ==================================================
% Tutorial 2 Solutions
% ==================================================

\subsection{Tutorial 2 Solutions - PART 1}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 8
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 8}

\begin{mainbox}

\textbf{Current carrier:}

A current carrier is a charged particle that contributes to electrical conduction in a material. In semiconductors, the current carriers are electrons and holes.

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{Hole:}

A hole is the absence of an electron in the valence band. It behaves as an effective positive charge carrier.

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{\(p\)-type / \(n\)-type semiconductor:}

A \(p\)-type semiconductor is formed by doping a semiconductor with acceptor atoms, producing holes as the majority carriers.

An \(n\)-type semiconductor is formed by doping with donor atoms, producing electrons as the majority carriers.

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{Intrinsic semiconductor:}

An intrinsic semiconductor is a pure semiconductor with no intentional doping. Electrons and holes are present in equal concentrations.

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 9
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 9}

\begin{mainbox}

For a semiconductor in thermal equilibrium,

\[
n_0 p_0 = n_i^2
\]

Since the material is \(p\)-type,

\[
p_0 > n_0
\]

Therefore,

\[
n_i^2 = n_0 p_0 > n_0^2
\]

Taking the square root gives

\[
n_i > n_0
\]

Hence,

\[
\boxed{
n_i > 2.0 \times 10^{10}\ \text{cm}^{-3}
}
\]

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 10
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 10}

\begin{mainbox}

The material is \(\boxed{p\text{-type}}\).

\vspace{0.4cm}

The Hall effect arises because moving charge carriers experience a magnetic force:

\[
\vec{F} = q\vec{v} \times \vec{B}
\]

The conventional current flows to the right, and the magnetic field points out of the page.

For positive charge carriers (holes), the magnetic force direction produces the observed positive Hall voltage.

Since the measured Hall voltage is positive, the dominant charge carriers are positive.

Therefore, the semiconductor is \(p\)-type.

\end{mainbox}

