\begin{greenbox}

\subsubsection*{Conceptual Question 17}

\textbf{Question}

True or False:
At any temperature, the Fermi energy is the energy level above which all electron states are empty.

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{Solution}

\[
\boxed{\text{False}}
\]

At absolute zero (\(T=0\,\text{K}\)),
all states above the Fermi energy are empty.

However, at temperatures above absolute zero,
some electrons gain thermal energy and occupy states above the Fermi energy.

Therefore, the Fermi energy is not an absolute boundary between filled and empty states at all temperatures.

\end{greenbox}

% ------------------------------------------------

\begin{greenbox}

\subsubsection*{Conceptual Question 18}

\textbf{Question}

Why does the conductivity of intrinsic semiconductors increase with temperature?

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{Solution}

\[
\boxed{
\text{(b) The number of free electrons and holes increases steeply with }T
}
\]

As temperature increases,
more electrons gain enough thermal energy to jump across the band gap from the valence band to the conduction band.

This creates:

\[
\text{more free electrons}
\]

and

\[
\text{more holes}
\]

which significantly increases conductivity.

Although collisions also increase with temperature,
the dramatic increase in carrier concentration dominates in intrinsic semiconductors.

\end{greenbox}

