\begin{greenbox}

\subsubsection*{Quantitative Question 19(c)}

\textbf{Question}

Suppose the material is at \(T=0\,\text{K}\)
and light with

\[
\lambda > \lambda_c
\]

is shined on the material.

Describe what happens.

\vspace{0.4cm}

\textbf{Solution}

If

\[
\lambda > \lambda_c
\]

then the photon energy is smaller than the band-gap energy because

\[
E=\frac{hc}{\lambda}
\]

and increasing wavelength decreases energy.

Therefore, the photons do not have enough energy to excite electrons from the valence band to the conduction band.

As a result:

\begin{itemize}

\item No electron-hole pairs are generated

\item No significant absorption occurs

\item The material remains non-conductive

\end{itemize}

\vspace{0.4cm}

\[
\boxed{
\text{Photons with }\lambda>\lambda_c
\text{ cannot excite electrons across the band gap.}
}
\]

\end{greenbox}
