% ------------------------------------------------
% Solution 25
% ------------------------------------------------

\begin{greenbox}

\subsubsection*{Solution 25}

When the Fermi level moves closer to the conduction band:

\[
E_F \rightarrow E_C
\]

the electron concentration increases.

From semiconductor statistics:

\[
n_0
=
N_C
e^{-(E_C-E_F)/k_BT}
\]

As

\[
E_C-E_F
\]

becomes smaller,
the exponential term becomes larger,
so the number of free electrons increases.

\vspace{0.5cm}

Conductivity is

\[
\sigma
=
en\mu_n
\]

Thus,
increasing electron concentration increases conductivity.

Since

\[
\rho
=
\frac{1}{\sigma}
\]

the resistivity decreases.

\vspace{0.5cm}

\[
\boxed{
\text{The resistivity decreases as }E_F
\text{ moves closer to }E_C
}
\]

\end{greenbox}

