\section{Practice Problems}
\subsection{Set #6}
\subsection*{Question 1}

\begin{mainbox}

\textbf{True or False:}

The formulas

\[
n_0 = N_c e^{-(E_c-E_F)/k_BT}
\]

and

\[
p_0 = N_v e^{-(E_F-E_v)/k_BT}
\]

do not include the effects of doping.

Explain your answer.

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 1
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 1}

\begin{mainbox}

\textbf{Answer: False}

\vspace{0.3cm}

The effects of doping are included indirectly through the Fermi energy level \(E_F\).

\vspace{0.3cm}

When donor or acceptor atoms are added to a semiconductor, the Fermi level shifts:

\begin{itemize}

\item In \(n\)-type material, \(E_F\) moves closer to the conduction band.

\item In \(p\)-type material, \(E_F\) moves closer to the valence band.

\end{itemize}

Since the carrier concentration formulas depend on \(E_F\), doping changes both \(n_0\) and \(p_0\).

Therefore, the statement is false.

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Question 2
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Question 2}

\begin{mainbox}

When donor atoms are introduced into a semiconductor sample, why does the equilibrium hole concentration decrease?

Explain in words.

\end{mainbox}

% --------------------------------------------------
% Solution 2
% --------------------------------------------------

\subsection*{Solution 2}

\begin{mainbox}

When donor atoms are added, extra electrons are introduced into the semiconductor.

These electrons recombine with holes, causing previously unoccupied states in the valence band to become occupied.

As a result, the equilibrium hole concentration decreases.

\vspace{0.3cm}

This is also consistent with the mass-action law:

\[
n_0 p_0 = n_i^2
\]

As the electron concentration \(n_0\) increases, the hole concentration \(p_0\) must decrease so that the product remains constant.

\end{mainbox}



